{"meta":{"domain":"subjects","kid":"5295","authors":[{"fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre","id":"6"}],"title":"","dates":{"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:50 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:15:50 UTC"}},"nodes":[{"index":0,"parent_index":-1,"body":"<p class=\"Paragraph\">Whereas this case<a href=\"#_ftn1\">[1]<\/a> is not used much in Spoken Tibetan, it is very common in the literary language. The associative <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> goes with a small class of verbs and adjectives, some of which occur quite frequently:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0fa1\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo possess\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0f45\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo possess\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f42\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo infringe,\u201d \u201cto go against\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f5a\u0f74\u0f44\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cComparable with\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f47\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo meet\u201d(H), <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f50\u0f74\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo meet\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f50\u0f74\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo be in agreement (with)\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0f9f\u0f74\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo agree,\u201d \u201cto harmonize\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f50\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo fight with\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f50\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f49\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo be close (to)\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f42\u0fb2\u0f7c\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo be associated with,\u201d \u201cto be accompanied by\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0fa6\u0fb2\u0f42\u0f66\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo tie\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0fa6\u0fb1\u0f62\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo stick\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0fb7\u0f53\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo be together\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f49\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo be (with)\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f60\u0f51\u0fb2\u0f7a\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo mingle (with)\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0fa6\u0fb2\u0f7a\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo connect,\u201d \u201cto attach\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f66\u0fa1\u0f7a\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo join\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f58\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f62\u0f92\u0fb1\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo make war (on\/against)\u201d <\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f56\u0fb2\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo be separated (from),\u201d \u201cto be deprived (of)\u201d<\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">Following are some example sentences using the associative:<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f53\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f63\u0f9f\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f50\u0f74\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f60\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f74\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f64\u0f72\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f7c\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cA time will come when there will be a philosophical position hostile to Buddhism.\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f58\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f5f\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f7c\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f50\u0f74\u0f42\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo meet an excellent person\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f41\u0fb2\u0f72\u0f58\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f42\u0f63\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f0b<\/span> \u201cTo break the law\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f68\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f61\u0f74\u0f51\u0f0b\u0f5a\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f5e\u0f72\u0f42\u0f0b\u0f55\u0fb2\u0f51\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cI shall meet my mother (if only) for an instant.\u201d<\/li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0fb7\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f72\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f63\u0fb7\u0f0b\u0f62\u0fa3\u0f58\u0f66\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f50\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f4f\u0f74\u0f0b\u0f60\u0f42\u0fb2\u0f7c<\/span> \u201cThe titans are going to make war on the gods.\u201d <\/li> <\/ul><p class=\"Paragraph\">As in Spoken Tibetan, the marker may also function as a coordinating conjunction, \u201cand\u201d (xxlink mst 9.3). It also acts as an imperative marker (xxlink mst 19.3). In Literary Tibetan, it is also used to introduce temporal clauses: \u201cas soon as, when.\u201d<\/p><ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f49\u0f72\u0f0b\u0f58\u0f0b\u0f64\u0f62\u0f0b\u0f56\u0f0b\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b\u0f55\u0fb1\u0f72\u0f53\u0f0b\u0f54\u0f0d<\/span> \u201cThey set off as soon as the sun rose.\u201d<\/li> <\/ul><hr size=\"1\" \/><p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\">[1]<\/a> In <em>The Classical Tibetan Language<\/em> (Albany: State University of New York Press, 1992), Stephan Beyer proposes that <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> be treated as a case, but he provides no arguments for his analysis, which is not supported by Tibetan grammars. However, the suggestion is a good one, and a number of arguments may be cited in support. <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> cannot be preceded or followed by any other case markers. In other dialects, such as Ladakhi, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> marks the instrumental and the associative. In Central Tibetan, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> may be replaced by other cases such as the oblique or the absolutive. Like all the other case markers, the absolutive, the genitive, the agentive, the ablative and the oblique, the associative marker has two kinds of functions: case-related and connective. It should also be noted that in Amdo, the usual marker that corresponds to the Central Tibetan <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> is <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f63\u0f0b<\/span>, which is also a case marker.<\/p><p>This being said, there are two features that give the associative a special character: \ufb01rst, contrary to other case markers, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> usually goes before the main verb, with which it has a close relation; and secondly, there are relatively few verbs that can take this marker, so that the case function of <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">\u0f51\u0f44\u0f0b<\/span> is rather rare.<\/p>","title":""}]}
