s=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྦྲེལ་</span> “To connect,” “to attach” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">སྡེབ་</span> “To join” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དམག་བརྒྱབ་</span> “To make war (on/against)” </li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">བྲལ་</span> “To be separated (from),” “to be deprived (of)”</li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">Following are some example sentences using the associative:</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ནང་པ་དང་ལྟ་བ་མི་མཐུན་པའི་དུས་ཤིག་ཡོང་།</span> “A time will come when there will be a philosophical position hostile to Buddhism.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">མི་བཟང་པོ་དང་ཐུག་</span> “To meet an excellent person”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཁྲིམས་དང་འགལ་བ་</span> “To break the law”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ང་ཨ་མ་དང་ཡུད་ཚམ་ཞིག་ཕྲད།</span> “I shall meet my mother (if only) for an instant.”</li> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལྷ་མིན་ལྷ་རྣམས་དང་འཐབ་ཏུ་འགྲོ</span> “The titans are going to make war on the gods.” </li> </ul> <p class=\"Paragraph\">As in Spoken Tibetan, the marker may also function as a coordinating conjunction, “and” (xxlink mst 9.3). It also acts as an imperative marker (xxlink mst 19.3). In Literary Tibetan, it is also used to introduce temporal clauses: “as soon as, when.”</p> <ul> <li><span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ཉི་མ་ཤར་བ་དང་ཕྱིན་པ།</span> “They set off as soon as the sun rose.”</li> </ul> <hr size=\"1\" /> <p><a href=\"#_ftnref1\">[1]</a> In <em>The Classical Tibetan Language</em> (Albany: State University of New York Press, 1992), Stephan Beyer proposes that <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དང་</span> be treated as a case, but he provides no arguments for his analysis, which is not supported by Tibetan grammars. However, the suggestion is a good one, and a number of arguments may be cited in support. <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དང་</span> cannot be preceded or followed by any other case markers. In other dialects, such as Ladakhi, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དང་</span> marks the instrumental and the associative. In Central Tibetan, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དང་</span> may be replaced by other cases such as the oblique or the absolutive. Like all the other case markers, the absolutive, the genitive, the agentive, the ablative and the oblique, the associative marker has two kinds of functions: case-related and connective. It should also be noted that in Amdo, the usual marker that corresponds to the Central Tibetan <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དང་</span> is <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">ལ་</span>, which is also a case marker.</p> <p>This being said, there are two features that give the associative a special character: ﬁrst, contrary to other case markers, <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དང་</span> usually goes before the main verb, with which it has a close relation; and secondly, there are relatively few verbs that can take this marker, so that the case function of <span class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\">དང་</span> is rather rare.</p>","title":""}]}
